Installing Software and data for Online R programming session

1. Install R and RStudio

  • Download R @ The R Project’s Home Page

    • Windows:
      • https://cloud.r-project.org/bin/windows/base/R-4.0.0-win.exe
    • Mac:
      • https://cloud.r-project.org/bin/macosx/R-4.0.0.pkg
    • Linux
      • https://cloud.r-project.org/bin/linux/

  • Download RStudio Desktop from RStudio

    • Windows
      • https://download1.rstudio.org/desktop/windows/RStudio-1.2.5042.exe
    • Mac
      • https://download1.rstudio.org/desktop/macos/RStudio-1.2.5042.dmg
    • Linux
      • https://www.rstudio.com/products/rstudio/download/#download

  • Run the installers for R and RStudio, in that order.

2. Open RStudio

It should look like this when you do:

3. Install additional packages and data

  • copy-paste the text below into the command window
  • hit enter
  • accept any defaults if you get prompted
  • this may take a little while (you don’t necessarily have to worry if there’s a lot of output messages)
install.packages(c("tidyverse", "sf", "devtools", "rgdal", "rgeos", "proj4"))
remotes::install_github("spatialanalysis/geodaData")

4. Test it out

Copy-paste the following text into the command window and hit enter.

  • If the picture shows up then you have installed all the necessary packages.
  • Don’t worry if you don’t understand the commands.
library(tidyverse)    
library(sf)
library(geodaData)

ggplot(data = geodaData::chicago_comm) + 
  geom_sf() + 
  ggtitle("Map of Chicago Community Areas")
